  "narrative": "<h3 class=\"story-subheading\">Short impact summary</h3>\n<p class=\"story-text\">Despite its publication in 2016, \"Forme(s) et modes d\u2019\u00eatre / Form(s) and Modes of Being\" has yet to garner citations or online discourse, reflecting a quiet reception in the scholarly community and beyond.</p>\n<h3 class=\"story-subheading\">Full narrative</h3>\n<p class=\"story-text\">Published by Peter Lang B in 2016, \"Forme(s) et modes d\u2019\u00eatre / Form(s) and Modes of Being\" currently holds a notable position as a pedagogical anchor with a heuristic strength of 0.9. This suggests that it has the potential to be used in educational settings, particularly as an academic resource in relevant courses or programs.</p>\n<p class=\"story-text\">The book has been associated with commercial linkages, reported to be available on platforms such as Amazon and Goodreads, indicating some level of accessibility for interested readers. These platforms provide opportunities for potential readership and engagement with its themes.</p>\n<p class=\"story-text\">While no substantial community discourse has emerged on platforms such as Wikipedia, Reddit, Bluesky, or through Hypothesis annotations, this absence suggests that the book has not yet penetrated broader public discussions or gained traction in contemporary debates related to its subject matter.</p>\n<p class=\"story-text\">The data pertaining to this work shows a promising potential for its role as a resource in academic curricula. However, the lack of citations and online engagement points to a need for further exploration and dialogue around its concepts to enhance its impact and reach within scholarly and public spheres.</p>",
